These Townsend's Big-eared Bats were two of around a dozen peppered around a small section of cave at Pinnacles National Monument. This is one of the beauties of going to the Pinnacles early in the morning on a weekday. There haven't been lots of people walking around and the wildlife is often much more accessible. 

They were roosting on the cave walls. After I saw them,  I slowly raised my flashlight up, took a few pictures, and then slowly dropped the light. The bats didn't move and an hour later were still in the same place. 

Their identification was based on their very long ears (folded back), long, sharp tragus, and the raised glands on either side of their noses.

Western Grey Squirrels (Sciurus griseus) remain fairly common in the Redwood and riparian sections of Big Sur. description: I was enjoying a lunch on the back deck of River View Restaurant & Lounge when I seen these small birds flying from their perches in the trees to rocks on the edge and in the middle of the river. When the bird would land on the rocks that were precariously close to the water's torrent they would edge themselves closer and closer to the edge. Then all of a sudden "bloop" the little bird was gone, and instantly I knew what I was observing. I had never seen an American dipper before, but I am not aware of too many birds that have that behavior. I was amazed by their boldness, being able to dive into what I perceived to be a rapid current of water didn't seem to phase the little bird at all.

description: Liquidambar has to be one of the most widely planted trees in Oakland and also one of the most troublesome. Every rainy season I witness dozens of these trees losing large limbs, or entire trees falling down. I figure Oakland plants them cause they do well in the cityscape and are drought tolerant. Still, when the rain comes the trees with cuts or injuries soak up the water into their heartwood turning it into a pulpy mush. Pulpy mush not being the most structurally sound material the weight of the tree or limb comes crashing down. They are also a untidy tree laying down tons of small spiked capsules which can be dangerous on concrete sidewalks as they roll under your feet.

description:
I had great fun watching a river otter this afternoon (12/11/11) at Healdsburg Ridge Open Space Preserve. It spent much of an hour energetically swimming around Fox Pond in pursuit of food, occasionally going to shore to feast on its unfortunate victims. I just loved tracking its underwater movement by following the trail of air bubbles, and hearing its inhalations during brief trips to the surface. The highlight was watching it chow down on a big fish - I could even hear crunching! What a treat!!  It was at the pond yesterday as well.

Update (1/13/12):  Saw the river otter at Fox Pond today, my first time visiting the pond since I first reported the otter back in December.  I heard it was there a week after I reported it as well.  I'm surprised it hasn't exhausted its food supply yet.  It was eating something when I arrived, but it soon disappeared.
